# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-container-apps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containerization originated several centuries ago but was not well developed or widely applied until after World War II, when it dramatically reduced the costs of transport, supported the post-war boom in international trade, and was a major element in globalization.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containerization eliminated manual sorting of most shipments and the need for dock front warehouses, while displacing many thousands of dock workers who formerly simply handled break bulk cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containerization reduced congestion in ports, significantly shortened shipping time, and reduced losses from damage and theft.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers can be made from a wide range of materials such as steel, fibre-reinforced polymer, aluminum or a combination.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers made from weathering steel are used to minimize maintenance needs.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Before containerization, goods were usually handled manually as break bulk cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Typically, goods would be loaded onto a vehicle from the factory and taken to a port warehouse where they would be offloaded and stored awaiting the next vessel.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] When the vessel arrived, they would be moved to the side of the ship along with other cargo to be lowered or carried into the hold and packed by dock workers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The ship might call at several other ports before off-loading a given consignment of cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Each port visit would delay the delivery of other cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Delivered cargo might then have been offloaded into another warehouse before being picked up and delivered to its destination.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Multiple handling and delays made transport costly, time-consuming and unreliable.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containerization has its origins in early coal mining regions in England beginning in the late 18th century.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1766 James Brindley designed the "starvationer" box boat with ten wooden containers, to transport coal from Worsley Delph (quarry) to Manchester by Bridgewater Canal.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1795, Benjamin Outram opened the Little Eaton Gangway, upon which coal was carried in wagons built at his Butterley Ironwork.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The horse-drawn wheeled wagons on the gangway took the form of containers, which, loaded with coal, could be transshipped from canal barges on the Derby Canal, which Outram had also promoted.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By the 1830s, railroads were carrying containers that could be transferred to other modes of transport.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The Liverpool and Manchester Railway in the UK was one of these, making use of "simple rectangular timber boxes" to convey coal from Lancashire collieries to Liverpool, where a crane transferred them to horse-drawn carriages.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Originally used for moving coal on and off barges, "loose boxes" were used to containerize coal from the late 1780s, at places like the Bridgewater Canal.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By the 1840s, iron boxes were in use as well as wooden ones.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The early 1900s saw the adoption of closed container boxes designed for movement between road and rail.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] On 17 May 1917, Louisville, Kentucky, native Benjamin Franklin "B.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] F." Fitch (1877–1956) launched commercial use of "demountable bodies" in Cincinnati, Ohio, which he had designed as transferable containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1919, his system was extended to over 200 containers serving 21 railway stations with 14 freight trucks.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1919, engineer Stanisław Rodowicz developed the first draft of the container system in Poland.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1920, he built a prototype of the biaxial wagon.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The Polish-Bolshevik War stopped development of the container system in Poland.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Post Office contracted with the New York Central Railroad to move mail via containers in May 1921.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1926, a regular connection of the luxury passenger train from London to Paris, Golden Arrow/Fleche d'Or, by Southern Railway and French Northern Railway, began.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For transport of passengers' baggage four containers were used.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] These containers were loaded in London or Paris and carried to ports, Dover or Calais, on flat cars in the UK and "CIWL Pullman Golden Arrow Fourgon of CIWL" in France.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Beginning in March 1928 the Pennsylvania Railroad (PRR) introduced an extensive container service network connecting New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, South Kearney, New Jersey, Buffalo, Cleveland and Pittsburg.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] At the Second World Motor Transport Congress in Rome, September 1928, Italian senator Silvio Crespi proposed the use of containers for road and railway transport systems, using collaboration rather than competition.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This would be done under the auspices of an international organ similar to the Sleeping Car Company, which provided international carriage of passengers in sleeping wagons.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] After the Wall Street crash of 1929 in New York and the subsequent Great Depression, many countries were without any means to transport cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The railroads were sought as a possibility to transport cargo, and there was an opportunity to bring containers into broader use.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] From April 1930 Japan began using steel containers with capacity of 60 feet an dimensions 6,5 feet long, 2,3 feet wide, and 2,5 feet high with weigth not exceed 50 kg.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] They were used in the Tokaido highway line between Kobe,Tokyo, Osaka, Nagoya, and Yokohama.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Also for transport food and clothing containers were between Ashikaga, Kiryu, Ashihabara, Hachiozi, Shinjuku, Nagoya, Umekouzi, and Osaka.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1930, the Chicago & Northwestern Railroad began shipping containers between Chicago and Milwaukee.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Their efforts ended in the spring of 1931 when the Interstate Commerce Commission disallowed the use of a flat rate for the containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In February 1931 the first container ship was launched.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It was called the Autocarrier, owned by Southern Railway UK.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It had 21 slots for containers of Southern Railway.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Under auspices of the International Chamber of Commerce in Paris in Venice on September 30, 1931, on one of the platforms of the Maritime Station (Mole di Ponente), practical tests assessed the best construction for European containers as part of an international competition.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Fitch designed the two largest and heaviest containers in existence.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In November 1932, in Enola, Pennsylvania, the first container terminal in the world was opened by the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The Fitch hooking system was used for reloading of the containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1933 in Europe, under the auspices of the International Chamber of Commerce, the International Container Bureau (French: *Bureau International des Conteneurs*, B.I.C.) was established.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In June 1933, the B.I.C. decided on obligatory parameters for containers used in international traffic.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers handled by means of lifting gear, such as cranes, overhead conveyors, etc. for traveling elevators (group I containers), constructed after July 1, 1933.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] From 1926 to 1947 in the U.S., the Chicago North Shore and Milwaukee Railway carried motor carrier vehicles and shippers' vehicles loaded on flatcars between Milwaukee, Wisconsin, and Chicago, Illinois.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Beginning in 1929, Seatrain Lines carried railroad boxcars on its sea vessels to transport goods between New York and Cuba.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the mid-1930s, the Chicago Great Western Railway and then the New Haven Railroad began "piggyback" service (transporting highway freight trailers on flatcars) limited to their own railroads.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The Chicago Great Western Railway filed a U.S. patent in 1938 on their method of securing trailers to a flatcars using chains and turnbuckles.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Other components included wheel chocks and ramps for loading and unloading the trailers from the flatcars.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By 1953, the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy, the Chicago and Eastern Illinois, and the Southern Pacific railroads had joined the innovation.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Most of the rail cars used were surplus flatcars equipped with new decks.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By 1955, an additional 25 railroads had begun some form of piggyback trailer service.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] During World War II, the Australian Army used containers to more easily deal with various breaks of gauge in the railroads.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] These non-stackable containers were about the size of the later 20-foot ISO container and perhaps made mainly of wood.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] During the same time, the United States Army started to combine items of uniform size, lashing them onto a pallet, unitizing cargo to speed the loading and unloading of transport ships.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1947 the Transportation Corps developed the *Transporter*, a rigid, corrugated steel container with a 9,000 lb (4,100 kg) carrying capacity, for shipping household goods of officers in the field.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It was 8 ft 6 in (2.59 m) long, 6 ft 3 in (1.91 m), and 6 ft 10 in (2.08 m) high, with double doors on one end, mounted on skids, and had lifting rings on the top four corners.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] During the Korean War the Transporter was evaluated for handling sensitive military equipment and, proving effective, was approved for broader use.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Theft of material and damage to wooden crates convinced the army that steel containers were needed.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In April 1951, at Zürich Tiefenbrunnen railway station, the Swiss Museum of Transport and *Bureau International des Containers* (BIC) held demonstrations of container systems, with the aim of selecting the best solution for Western Europe.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Present were representatives from France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, Switzerland, Sweden, Great Britain, Italy and the United States.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The system chosen for Western Europe was based on the Netherlands' system for consumer goods and waste transportation called *Laadkisten* (literally, "loading bins"), in use since 1934.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This system used roller containers that were moved by rail, truck and ship, in various configurations up to a capacity of 5,500 kg (12,100 lb), and up to 3.1 by 2.3 by 2 metres (10 ft 2 in × 7 ft 6+1⁄2 in × 6 ft 6+3⁄4 in) size.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This became the first post World War II European railway standard UIC 590, known as "pa-Behälter." It was implemented in the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, West Germany, Switzerland, Sweden and Denmark.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] With the popularization of the larger ISO containers, support for pa containers was phased out by the railways.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the 1970s they began to be widely used for transporting waste.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Army developed the Transporter into the CONtainer EXpress or CONEX box system.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The size and capacity of the CONEXes were about the same as the Transporter, but the system was made *modular*, by the addition of a smaller, half-size unit of 6 ft 3 in (1.91 m) long, 4 ft 3 in (1.30 m) wide and 6 ft 10+1⁄2 in (2.10 m) high.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] CONEXes could be stacked three high, and protected their contents from the elements.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The first major shipment of CONEXes, containing engineering supplies and spare parts, was made by rail from the Columbus General Depot in Georgia to the Port of San Francisco, then by ship to Yokohama, Japan, and then to Korea, in late 1952.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By the time of the Vietnam War the majority of supplies and materials were shipped by CONEX.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By 1965 the U.S. military used some 100,000 CONEX boxes, and more than 200,000 in 1967. making this the first worldwide application of intermodal containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] After the US Department of Defense standardized an 8-by-8-foot (2.44 by 2.44 m) cross section container in multiples of 10-foot (3.05 m) lengths for military use, it was rapidly adopted for shipping purposes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1955, former trucking company owner Malcom McLean worked with engineer Keith Tantlinger to develop the modern intermodal container.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] All the containerization pioneers who came before McLean had thought in terms of optimizing particular modes of transport.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] McLean's "fundamental insight" which made the intermodal container possible was that the core business of the shipping industry "was moving cargo, not sailing ships".
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] He visualized and helped to bring about a world reoriented around that insight, which required not just standardization of the metal containers themselves, but drastic changes to *every* aspect of cargo handling.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 1955, McLean and Tantlinger's immediate challenge was to design a shipping container that could efficiently be loaded onto ships and would hold securely on sea voyages.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The result was an 8-foot-tall (2.44 m) by 8 ft-wide (2.44 m) box in 10 ft-long (3.05 m) units constructed from 2.5 mm-thick (13⁄128 in) corrugated steel.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The design incorporated a twistlock mechanism atop each of the four corners, allowing the container to be easily secured and lifted using cranes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Several years later, as a Fruehauf executive, Tantlinger went back to McLean and convinced him to relinquish control of their design to help stimulate the container revolution.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] On January 29, 1963, McLean's company SeaLand released its patent rights, so that Tantlinger's inventions could become "the basis for a standard corner fitting and twist lock".
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This began international standardization of shipping containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The first vessels purpose-built to carry containers had begun operation in 1926 for the regular connection of the luxury passenger train between London and Paris, the Golden Arrow/Fleche d'Or.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Four containers were used for the conveyance of passengers' baggage.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] These containers were loaded in London or Paris and carried to the ports of Dover or Calais.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In February 1931 the first container ship in the world was launched.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It was called the Autocarrier, owned by the UK's Southern Railway.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The next step was in Europe after World War II.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Vessels purpose-built to carry containers were used between UK and Netherlands and also in Denmark in 1951.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the United States, ships began carrying containers in 1951, between Seattle, Washington, and Alaska.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] None of these services was particularly successful.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] First, the containers were rather small, with 52% of them having a volume of less than 3 cubic metres (106 cu ft).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Almost all European containers were made of wood and used canvas lids, and they required additional equipment for loading into rail or truck bodies.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The world's first purpose-built container vessel was *Clifford J.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Rodgers*, built in Montreal in 1955 and owned by the White Pass and Yukon Corporation.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Her first trip carried 600 containers between North Vancouver, British Columbia, and Skagway, Alaska, on November 26, 1955.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In Skagway, the containers were unloaded to purpose-built railroad cars for transport north to Yukon, in the first intermodal service using trucks, ships, and railroad cars.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Southbound containers were loaded by shippers in Yukon and moved by rail, ship, and truck to their consignees without opening.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This first intermodal system operated from November 1955 until 1982.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The first truly successful container shipping company dates to April 26, 1956, when American trucking entrepreneur McLean put 58 *trailer vans* later called containers, aboard a refitted tanker ship, the SS *Ideal X*, and sailed them from Newark, New Jersey, to Houston, Texas.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Independently of the events in Canada, McLean had the idea of using large containers that never opened in transit and that were transferable on an intermodal basis, among trucks, ships, and railroad cars.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] McLean had initially favored the construction of "trailerships"—taking trailers from large trucks and stowing them in a ship's cargo hold.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This method of stowage, referred to as roll-on/roll-off, was not adopted because of the large waste in potential cargo space on board the vessel, known as broken stowage.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Instead, McLean modified his original concept into loading just the containers, not the chassis, onto the ship; hence the designation "container ship" or "box" ship.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] During the first 20 years of containerization, many container sizes and corner fittings were used.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] There were dozens of incompatible container systems in the US alone.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Among the biggest operators, the Matson Navigation Company had a fleet of 24-foot (7.32 m) containers, while Sea-Land Service, Inc used 35-foot (10.67 m) containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The standard sizes and fitting and reinforcement norms that now exist evolved out of a lengthy and complex series of compromises among international shipping companies, European railroads, US railroads, and US trucking companies.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For example, to McLean's frustration, Sea-Land's 35-foot container was not adopted as one of the standard container sizes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Based on these standards, the first TEU container ship was the Japanese *Hakone Maru* from shipowner NYK, which started sailing in 1968 and could carry 752 TEU containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the US, containerization and other advances in shipping were impeded by the Interstate Commerce Commission (ICC), which was created in 1887 to keep railroads from using monopolist pricing and rate discrimination, but fell victim to regulatory capture.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] By the 1960s, ICC approval was required before any shipper could carry different items in the same vehicle or change rates.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The fully integrated systems in the US today became possible only after the ICC's regulatory oversight was cut back (and abolished in 1995).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Trucking and rail were deregulated in the 1970s and maritime rates were deregulated in 1984.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Double-stacked rail transport, where containers are stacked two high on railway cars, was introduced in the US.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The concept was developed by Sea-Land and the Southern Pacific railroad.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The first standalone double-stack container car (or single-unit 40-foot (12.2 m) COFC well car) was delivered in July 1977.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The five-unit well car, the industry standard, appeared in 1981.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Initially, these double-stack railway cars were deployed in regular train service.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Ever since American President Lines initiated in 1984 a dedicated double-stack container train service between Los Angeles and Chicago, transport volumes increased rapidly.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containerization greatly reduced the expense of international trade and increased its speed, especially of consumer goods and commodities.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It also dramatically changed the character of port cities worldwide.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Prior to highly mechanized container transfers, crews of 20 to 22 longshoremen would pack individual cargoes into the hold of a ship.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] After containerization, large crews of longshoremen were not necessary at port facilities, and the profession changed drastically.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Meanwhile, the port facilities needed to support containerization changed.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] One effect was the decline of some ports and the rise of others.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] At the Port of San Francisco, the former piers used for loading and unloading were no longer required, but there was little room to build the vast holding lots needed for storing and sorting containers in transit between different transport modes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] As a result, the Port of San Francisco essentially ceased to function as a major commercial port, but the neighboring Port of Oakland emerged as the second largest on the US West Coast.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] A similar fate occurred with the relationship between the ports of Manhattan and New Jersey.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the UK, the Port of London and Port of Liverpool declined in importance.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Meanwhile, Britain's Port of Felixstowe and Port of Rotterdam in the Netherlands emerged as major ports.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] With intermodal containers, the jobs of packing, unpacking, and sorting cargoes could be performed far from the point of embarkation.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Such work shifted to so-called "dry ports" and gigantic warehouses in rural inland towns, where land and labor were much cheaper than in oceanfront cities.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This fundamental transformation of where warehouse work was performed freed up valuable waterfront real estate near the central business districts of port cities around the world for redevelopment and led to a plethora of waterfront revitalization projects (such as warehouse districts).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The effects of containerization rapidly spread beyond the shipping industry.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers were quickly adopted by trucking and rail transport industries for cargo transport not involving sea transport.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Manufacturing also evolved to adapt to take advantage of containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Companies that once sent small consignments began grouping them into containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Many cargoes are now designed to precisely fit containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The reliability of containers made just in time manufacturing possible as component suppliers could deliver specific components on regular fixed schedules.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 2004, global container traffic was 354 million TEUs, of which 82 percent were handled by the world's top 100 container ports.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] As of 2009, approximately 90% of non-bulk cargo worldwide is moved by containers stacked on transport ships; 26% of all container transshipment is carried out in China.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For example, in 2009 there were 105,976,701 transshipments in China (both international and coastal, excluding Hong Kong), 21,040,096 in Hong Kong (which is listed separately), and only 34,299,572 in the United States.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 2005, some 18 million containers made over 200 million trips per year.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Some ships can carry over 14,500 twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU), such as the *Emma Mærsk*, 396 m (1,299 ft) long, launched in August 2006.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It has been predicted that, at some point, container ships will be constrained in size only by the depth of the Straits of Malacca, one of the world's busiest shipping lanes, linking the Indian Ocean to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This so-called Malaccamax size constrains a ship to dimensions of 470 m (1,542 ft) in length and 60 m (197 ft) wide.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Few foresaw the extent of the influence of containerization on the shipping industry.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Improved cargo security is an important benefit of containerization.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Once the cargo is loaded into a container, it is not touched again until it reaches its destination.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The cargo is not visible to casual viewers, and thus is less likely to be stolen.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Container doors are usually sealed so that tampering is more evident.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Some containers are fitted with electronic monitoring devices and can be remotely monitored for changes in air pressure, which happens when the doors are opened.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This reduced thefts that had long plagued the shipping industry.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Recent developments have focused on the use of intelligent logistics optimization to further enhance security.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The use of the same basic sizes of containers across the globe has lessened the problems caused by incompatible rail gauge sizes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The majority of the rail networks in the world operate on a 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) gauge track known as standard gauge, but some countries (such as Russia, India, Finland, and Lithuania) use broader gauges, while others in Africa and South America use narrower gauges.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The use of container trains in all these countries makes transshipment between trains of different gauges easier.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers have become a popular way to ship private cars and other vehicles overseas using 20- or 40-foot containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Unlike roll-on/roll-off vehicle shipping, personal effects can be loaded into the container with the vehicle, allowing easy international relocation.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In July, 2020, The Digital Container Shipping Association (DCSA), a non-profit group established to further digitalisation of container shipping technology standards, published standards for the digital exchange of operational vessel schedules (OVS).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Contrary to ocean shipping containers owned by the shippers, a persisting trend in the industry is for (new) units to be purchased by leasing companies.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 2021, the average time to unload a container in Asia was 27 seconds, the average time in Northern Europe was 46 seconds, and the average time in North America was 76 seconds.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] US domestic standard containers are generally 48 ft (14.63 m) and 53 ft (16.15 m) (rail and truck).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Container capacity is often expressed in twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU, or sometimes *teu*).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] An equivalent unit is a measure of containerized cargo capacity equal to one standard 20 ft (6.10 m) (length) × 8 ft (2.44 m) (width) container.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] As this is an approximate measure, the height of the box is not considered.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For instance, the 9 ft 6 in (2.90 m) *high cube* and the 4 ft 3 in (1.30 m) *half height* 20 ft (6.10 m) containers are also called one TEU.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] 48' containers have been phased out over the last ten years in favor of 53' containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The maximum gross mass for a 20 ft (6.10 m) dry cargo container was initially set at 24,000 kg (53,000 lb), and 30,480 kg (67,200 lb)for a 40 ft (12.19 m) container (including the 9 ft 6 in or 2.90 m high cube) .
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Allowing for the tare mass of the container, the maximum payload mass is therefore reduced to approximately 22,000 kg (49,000 lb) for 20 ft (6.10 m), and 27,000 kg (60,000 lb) for 40 ft (12.19 m) containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It was increased to 30,480 kg for the 20' in 2005, then further increased to a max of 36,000 kg for all sizes by the amendment 2 (2016) of the ISO standard 668 (2013).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The original choice of 8-foot (2.44 m) height for ISO containers was made in part to suit a large proportion of railway tunnels, though some had to be modified.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The current standard is eight feet six inches (2.59 m) high.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] With the arrival of even taller hi-cube containers at nine feet six inches (2.90 m) and double stacking rail cars, further enlargement of the rail loading gauge is proving necessary.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] While major airlines use containers that are custom designed for their aircraft and associated ground handling equipment the IATA has created a set of standard aluminium container sizes of up to 11.52 m3 (407 cu ft) in volume.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] A full container load (FCL) is an ISO standard container that is loaded and unloaded under the risk and account of one shipper and one consignee.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In practice, it means that the whole container is intended for one consignee.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] FCL container shipment tends to have lower freight rates than an equivalent weight of cargo in bulk.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Less-than-container load (LCL) is a shipment that is not large enough to fill a standard cargo container.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The abbreviation LCL formerly applied to "less than (railway) car load" for quantities of material from different shippers or for delivery to different destinations carried in a single railway car for efficiency.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] LCL freight was often sorted and redistributed into different railway cars at intermediate railway terminals en route to the final destination.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It can also be defined as "a consignment of cargo which is inefficient to fill a shipping container.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] It is grouped with other consignments for the same destination in a container at a container freight station".
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers are actively used for smuggling and trafficking illicit goods and people.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Drugs, antiques, weapons, undeclared merchandise, jewellery, human beings, wildlife, counterfeit products, as well as chemical, radioactive and biological materials, are illegally transported via containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Additionally, there are concerns about terrorists using containers to transport weapons of mass destruction (WMD).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] However, these concerns remain hypothetical.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] There are several ways in which illicit goods are smuggled.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] One method involves forging documents to make a container appear as legal cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Another method is inserting illegal goods into a legitimate shipment, mixing legal and illegal items together.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For example, in 2024, several shipments of drugs, either disguised as banana cargo or mixed with legal banana shipments, were discovered in Germany, Greece, Spain and Great Britain.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Criminal groups use legitimate fruit businesses as fronts for their narcotics operations, making fruit cargo a common method for concealing drugs.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Trafficking in wildlife parts, such as ivory, frequently involves altering the appearance of the goods.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For instance, ivory has been known to be cut into the shape of chocolate bars or painted the colour of wood to avoid detection during X-ray inspections.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Additionally, containers can be physically modified to hide illegal parcels, such as through the use of fake walls, secret compartments, hollowed-out rails, support beams and doors.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The lack of capacity at ports to inspect containers increases the likelihood of smuggled goods going undetected.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In African ports, especially West Africa, where most drug routes converge, only about 2% of all containers are inspected.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Similarly, European ports check just 2–10% of incoming containers, leaving the majority unscreened and creating opportunities for trafficking.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Nevertheless, there are a number of security measures in place, notably the Container Security Initiative (CSI), a post-9/11 US-led programme.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This initiative aims to pre-screen high-risk cargo before it reaches US territory.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] One of its primary goals is to prevent the smuggling of weapons of mass destruction (WMD).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Although the programme was initiated by the United States, by 2007, some 20 countries had signed a Memorandum of Understanding with the US, leading to the implementation of CSI measures at 58 ports around the world.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The CSI system includes non-intrusive pre-screening methods, such as X-ray and radiation screening, for high-risk cargo destined for the United States.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] As a result, more than 80% of containerised cargo bound for the United States is pre-screened.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers are intended to be used constantly, being loaded with new cargo for a new destination soon after emptied of previous cargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] This is not always possible, and in some cases, the cost of transporting an empty container to a place where it can be used is considered to be higher than the worth of the used container.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Shipping lines and container leasing companies have become expert at repositioning empty containers from areas of low or no demand, such as the US West Coast, to areas of high demand, such as China.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Repositioning within the port hinterland has also been the focus of recent logistics optimization work.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Damaged or retired containers may be recycled in the form of shipping container architecture, or the steel content salvaged.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In the summer of 2010, a worldwide shortage of containers developed as shipping increased after the recession, while new container production had largely ceased.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers occasionally fall from ships, usually during storms.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] According to media sources, between 2,000 and 10,000 containers are lost at sea each year.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The World Shipping Council states in a survey among freight companies that this claim is grossly excessive and calculated an average of 350 containers to be lost at sea each year, or 675 if including catastrophic events.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] For instance, on November 30, 2006, a container washed ashore on the Outer Banks of North Carolina, along with thousands of bags of its cargo of Doritos Chips.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers lost in rough waters are smashed by cargo and waves, and often sink quickly.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Although not all containers sink, they seldom float very high out of the water, making them a shipping hazard that is difficult to detect.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Freight from lost containers has provided oceanographers with unexpected opportunities to track global ocean currents, notably a cargo of Friendly Floatees.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 2007 the International Chamber of Shipping and the World Shipping Council began work on a code of practice for container storage, including crew training on parametric rolling, safer stacking, the marking of containers, and security for above-deck cargo in heavy swell.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] In 2011, the MV Rena ran aground off the coast of New Zealand.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] As the ship listed, some containers were lost, while others were held on board at a precarious angle.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Some of the biggest battles in the container revolution were waged in Washington, D.C..
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Intermodal shipping got a huge boost in the early 1970s, when carriers won permission to quote combined rail-ocean rates.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Later, non-vessel-operating common carriers won a long court battle with a US Supreme Court decision against contracts that attempted to require that union labor be used for stuffing and stripping containers at off-pier locations.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers are often infested with pests.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Pest introductions are significantly clustered around ports, and containers are a common source of such successful pest transfers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The IPPC Sea Container Task Force (SCTF) promulgates the Cargo Transport Units Code (CTU), prescribed pesticides and other standards (see § Other container system standards) and recommendations for use in container decontamination, inspection and quarantine.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The SCTF also provides the English translation of the National Standard of China (GB/T 39919-2021).
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Shipping container architecture is the use of containers as the basis for housing and other functional buildings for people, either as temporary or a permanent housing, and either as a main building or as a cabin or as a workshop.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers can also be used as sheds or storage areas in industry and commerce.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Tempo Housing in Amsterdam stacks containers for individual housing units.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers are also beginning to be used to house computer data centers, although these are normally specialized containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] There is now a high demand for containers to be converted in the domestic market to serve specific purposes.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Containers are also converted to provide equipment enclosures, pop-up cafes, exhibition stands, security huts and more.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] Public containerised transport is the concept, not yet implemented, of modifying motor vehicles to serve as personal containers in non-road passenger transport.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] The ACTS roller container standards have become the basis of containerized firefighting equipment throughout Europe.
[src:azure-container-apps/containerization] On September 5, 2008, the BBC embarked on a year-long project to study international trade and globalization by tracking a shipping container on its journey around the world.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:azure-container-apps/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:azure-container-apps/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An *event* can be defined as "a significant change in state".
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] For example, when a consumer purchases a car, the car's state changes from "for sale" to "sold".
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] A car dealer's system architecture may treat this state change as an event whose occurrence can be made known to other applications within the architecture.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] From a formal perspective, what is produced, published, propagated, detected or consumed is a (typically asynchronous) message called the event notification, and not the event itself, which is the state change that triggered the message emission.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] However, the term *event* is often used metonymically to denote the notification message itself, which may lead to some confusion.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This is due to Event-driven architectures often being designed atop **message-driven architectures**, where such a communication pattern requires one of the inputs to be text-only, the message, to differentiate how each communication should be handled.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This architectural pattern may be applied by the design and implementation of applications and systems that transmit events among loosely coupled software components and services.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven system typically consists of event emitters (or agents), event consumers (or sinks), and event channels.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Emitters have the responsibility to detect, gather, and transfer events.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An Event Emitter does not know the consumers of the event, it does not even know if a consumer exists, and in case it exists, it does not know how the event is used or further processed.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Sinks have the responsibility of applying a reaction as soon as an event is presented.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The reaction might or might not be completely provided by the sink itself.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] For instance, the sink might just have the responsibility to filter, transform and forward the event to another component or it might provide a self-contained reaction to such an event.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event channels are conduits in which events are transmitted from event emitters to event consumers.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The knowledge of the correct distribution of events is exclusively present within the event channel.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The physical implementation of event channels can be based on traditional components such as message-oriented middleware or point-to-point communication which might require a more appropriate transactional executive framework.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Building systems around an event-driven architecture simplifies horizontal scalability in distributed computing models and makes them more resilient to failure.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This is because application state can be copied across multiple parallel snapshots for high-availability.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] New events can be initiated anywhere, but more importantly propagate across the network of data stores updating each as they arrive.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Adding extra nodes becomes trivial as well: you can simply take a copy of the application state, feed it a stream of events and run with it.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architecture can complement service-oriented architecture (SOA) because services can be activated by triggers fired on incoming events.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This paradigm is particularly useful whenever the sink does not provide any self-contained executive.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] SOA 2.0 evolves the implications SOA and EDA architectures provide to a richer, more robust level by leveraging previously unknown causal relationships to form a new event pattern.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This new business intelligence pattern triggers further autonomous human or automated processing that adds exponential value to the enterprise by injecting value-added information into the recognized pattern which could not have been achieved previously.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture has two primary topologies.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] With “broker topology”, components broadcast events to the entire system without any orchestrator.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides higher performance and scalability.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] With “mediator topology”, there is a central orchestrator which controls workflow of events.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides better control and error handling capabilities.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] You can also use a hybrid model and combine these two topologies.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] There are different types of events in EDA, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An event can be made of two parts, the event header and the event body also known as event payload.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The event header might include information such as event name, time stamp for the event, and type of event.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The event payload provides the details of the state change detected.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An event body should not be confused with the pattern or the logic that may be applied in reaction to the occurrence of the event itself.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This method involves including only keys or IDs, allowing consumers to fetch the required data from external data sources, such as databases.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] While this approach is less scalable and slower due to the need for database queries, it minimizes bandwidth usage and reduces coupling issues.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] These methods represent two ends of a spectrum rather than binary choices.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Architects must carefully size the event payloads to meet the specific needs of event consumers.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] In event driven architectures, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The first logical layer is the event producer, which senses a fact and represents that fact as an event message.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] As an example, an event producer could be an email client, an E-commerce system, a monitoring agent or some type of physical sensor.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Converting the data collected from such a diverse set of data sources to a single standardized form of data for evaluation is a significant task in the design and implementation of this first logical layer.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] However, considering that an event is a strongly declarative frame, any informational operations can be easily applied, thus eliminating the need for a high level of standardization.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An event channel is a mechanism of propagating the information collected from an event generator to the event engine or sink.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This could be a TCP/IP connection, or any type of an input file (flat, XML format, e-mail, etc.).
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Several event channels can be opened at the same time.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Usually, because the event processing engine has to process them in near real time, the event channels will be read asynchronously.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The events are stored in a queue, waiting to be processed later by the event processing engine.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The event processing engine is the logical layer responsible for identifying an event, and then selecting and executing the appropriate reaction.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] It can also trigger a number of assertions.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] For example, if the event that comes into the event processing engine is a product ID low in stock, this may trigger reactions such as “Order product ID” and “Notify personnel”.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This is the logical layer where the consequences of the event are shown.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This can be done in many different ways and forms; e.g., an email is sent to someone and an application may display some kind of warning on the screen.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Depending on the level of automation provided by the sink (event processing engine) the downstream activity might not be required.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] There are three general styles of event processing: simple, stream, and complex.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The three styles are often used together in a mature event-driven architecture.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing concerns events that are directly related to specific, measurable changes of condition.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] In simple event processing, a notable event happens which initiates downstream action(s).
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of work, thereby reducing lag time and cost.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] For example, simple events can be created by a sensor detecting changes in tire pressures or ambient temperature.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The car's tire incorrect pressure will generate a simple event from the sensor that will trigger a yellow light advising the driver about the state of a tire.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] In event stream processing (ESP), both ordinary and notable events happen.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Ordinary events (orders, RFID transmissions) are screened for notability and streamed to information subscribers.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event stream processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of information in and around the enterprise, which enables in-time decision making.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing (CEP) allows patterns of simple and ordinary events to be considered to infer that a complex event has occurred.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing evaluates a confluence of events and then takes action.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The events (notable or ordinary) may cross event types and occur over a long period of time.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The event correlation may be causal, temporal, or spatial.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] CEP requires the employment of sophisticated event interpreters, event pattern definition and matching, and correlation techniques.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] CEP is commonly used to detect and respond to business anomalies, threats, and opportunities.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Online event processing (OLEP) uses asynchronous distributed event logs to process complex events and manage persistent data.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] OLEP allows reliably composing related events of a complex scenario across heterogeneous systems.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] It thereby enables very flexible distribution patterns with high scalability and offers strong consistency.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] However, it cannot guarantee upper bounds on processing time.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven architecture is extremely loosely coupled and well distributed.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The great distribution of this architecture exists because an event can be almost anything and exist almost anywhere.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The architecture is extremely loosely coupled because the event itself doesn't know about the consequences of its cause. e.g.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] If we have an alarm system that records information when the front door opens, the door itself doesn't know that the alarm system will add information when the door opens, just that the door has been opened.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architectures have loose coupling within space, time and synchronization, providing a scalable infrastructure for information exchange and distributed workflows.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] However, event-architectures are tightly coupled, via event subscriptions and patterns, to the semantics of the underlying event schema and values.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] The high degree of semantic heterogeneity of events in large and open deployments such as smart cities and the sensor web makes it difficult to develop and maintain event-based systems.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] In order to address semantic coupling within event-based systems the use of approximate semantic matching of events is an active area of research.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture is susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Finding the right balance in the number of events can be quite difficult.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Generating too many detailed events can overwhelm the system, making it hard to analyze the overall event flow effectively.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This challenge becomes even greater when rollbacks are required.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Conversely, if events are overly consolidated, it can lead to unnecessary processing and responses from event consumers.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] To achieve an optimal balance, Mark Richards recommends to consider the impact of each event and whether consumers need to review the event payloads to determine their actions.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] For instance, in a compliance check scenario, it may be adequate to publish just two types of events: compliant and non-compliant.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] This method ensures that each event is only processed by the relevant consumers, reducing unnecessary workload.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] One of the challenges of using event driven architecture is error handling.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] One way to address this issue is to use a separate error-handler processor.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] So, when the event consumer experiences an error, it immediately and asynchronously sends the erroneous event to the error-handler processor and moves on.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Error-handler processor tries to fix the error and sends the event back to the original channel.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] But if the error-handler processor fails, then it can send the erroneous event to an administrator for further inspection.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Note that if you use an error-handler processor, erroneous events will be processed out of sequence when they are resubmitted.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] Another challenge of using event driven architecture is data loss.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] If any of the components crashes before successfully processing and handing over the event to its next component, then the event is dropped and never makes it into the final destination.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] To minimize the chance of data loss, you can persist in-transit events and remove / dequeue the events only when the next component has acknowledged the receipt of the event.
[src:azure-container-apps/event-driven-architecture] These features are usually known as "client acknowledge mode" and "last participant support".
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:azure-container-apps/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:azure-container-apps/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
